    <a title="Valeria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17242280-valeria"><img alt="Valeria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1455972717p2/17242280.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3696924261?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Valeria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Valeria" href="/user/show/17242280-valeria">Valeria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781613820315" href="/book/show/11321778-cyrano-de-bergerac">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3696924261" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15405618402406610383">What an enjoyable read this was. Maybe because I haven&apos;t expected it to be so, maybe because except the grotesque nose I knew nothing about this play, maybe because Cyrano proved himself to be interesting, eloquent, funny and gentle.<a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[ Yet the depth of his insecurity was so great, forcing him to live on crumbs and not even try to reach for the real thing.<br/>As story went and he started writing letters instead of his rival I remembered my personal experience about men pretending to be s</span></span>
  <span id="freeText15405618402406610383" style="display:none">What an enjoyable read this was. Maybe because I haven't expected it to be so, maybe because except the grotesque nose I knew nothing about this play, maybe because Cyrano proved himself to be interesting, eloquent, funny and gentle.<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ Yet the depth of his insecurity was so great, forcing him to live on crumbs and not even try to reach for the real thing.<br />As story went and he started writing letters instead of his rival I remembered my personal experience about men pretending to be somebody they are not just to win the lady; how rarely something good comes out of it. In this particular story it was tragic for all the main characters. Christian, in the last minutes of his life learns that he is not loved; Cyrano, with good intentions helps Roxane to stay in mourning for something that never existed and he himself was satisfied with being admirer instead of object of love. <br />I love Cyrano's character but I blame him that Roxane didn't have any say in the story. Being a woman she could have shed a different light on their potential mutual future; but if not that, she needn't spent fifteen years in solitude, she could have had choice. Christian had it, not quite but definitely more then her. <br />Clever and passionate, Cyrano was, sadly, led by his nose instead of his wits and heart.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
